      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Review Distribution, Review Spread</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Review diversity</strong> is having customer reviews distributed across multiple platforms rather than concentrated on a single source like Google. It distinguishes between narrow concentration (200 Google reviews, nothing elsewhere) and balanced distribution across Google, Yelp, Facebook, and industry-specific directories — each platform providing independent signals to search engines and potential customers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recommended Google split</div>
            <div class="tms-value">60–70% of efforts</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO / ORM</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Minimum platforms</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4–5 active</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If all your reviews live on Google and Google filters 30 of them tomorrow, your reputation takes a visible hit. Review diversity is the risk management play that most local businesses skip — until they need it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is review diversity?</h2>
        <p>Review diversity is both a local SEO strategy and a reputation risk management practice. On the SEO side, Google's local ranking algorithm considers review signals from third-party platforms — not just Google Reviews — when determining business prominence. Moz's Local Search Ranking Factors research confirms review diversity as a meaningful ranking signal.</p>
        <p>On the risk side, concentrating all reviews on one platform creates a single point of failure. If Google's algorithm flags your reviews, if the platform's policy changes, or if a competitor files a bulk takedown request, diversified reviews survive where a concentrated profile doesn't.</p>
        <p>The practical distinction:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Narrow concentration:</strong> 200 Google reviews, 2 Yelp reviews, nothing on Facebook or industry platforms</li>
          <li><strong>Balanced distribution:</strong> 120 Google reviews, 40 Yelp reviews, 25 Facebook reviews, 25 industry-specific platform reviews</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Both businesses have 185–200 total reviews. The diversified one is more resilient to platform changes and sends broader citation signals to Google.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google uses third-party review data</div>
          <p>Google evaluates review data from Yelp, BBB, and industry-specific platforms when assessing business prominence for local pack inclusion. Having reviews only on Google means Google has fewer independent signals to cross-reference for your credibility.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why review diversity matters for local businesses</h2>
        <p>Four reasons review diversity belongs in every local marketing strategy.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Multi-platform visibility drives independent traffic.</strong> Yelp, TripAdvisor, Healthgrades, and Avvo each send search traffic to your profile independently. A well-reviewed Yelp listing brings customers who never searched on Google at all.</li>
          <li><strong>Platform risk mitigation.</strong> Algorithm changes, policy updates, and bulk review removals happen on every platform. A restaurant with 400 Google reviews and 2 Yelp reviews is one algorithm update away from a reputation gap. A diversified profile continues operating normally.</li>
          <li><strong>Broader citation signals reinforce local SEO.</strong> Multiple platforms reviewing your business each become a citation — a mention of your business name, address, and phone — and a review signal. Both strengthen local organic rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Consumer trust from consistent cross-platform feedback.</strong> A buyer who sees 4.8 stars on Google checks Yelp and Facebook to confirm. When those match, trust increases. When only Google has reviews and others are empty, sophisticated buyers notice and question authenticity.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to build review diversity for your business</h2>
        <p>Review diversity requires a platform strategy, a request system, and monitoring — in that order.</p>

        <h3>Which platforms to target by industry</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Universal platforms (all businesses)</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Google Business Profile</span> → <span class="uf-label">Priority 1</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Yelp</span> → <span class="uf-label">Priority 2</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Facebook</span> → <span class="uf-label">Priority 3</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Apple Business Connect</span> → <span class="uf-label">Priority 4 (growing fast)</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Industry-specific platforms</span><br>
          Healthcare: <span class="uf-new">Healthgrades, Zocdoc, WebMD</span><br>
          Legal: <span class="uf-new">Avvo, Martindale-Hubbell</span><br>
          Home Services: <span class="uf-new">Houzz, Angi, HomeAdvisor</span><br>
          Hospitality: <span class="uf-new">TripAdvisor, Booking.com</span><br>
          Software / B2B: <span class="uf-new">G2, Capterra, Trustpilot</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Distributing review requests</h3>
        <p>A practical allocation that doesn't overwhelm your customers with choice:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Send <strong>60% of review requests</strong> to Google — it's the highest-impact platform for local pack rankings</li>
          <li>Send <strong>20% to Yelp</strong> — note that Yelp discourages direct solicitation; make it easy to find rather than actively requesting</li>
          <li>Send <strong>20% to your industry-specific platform</strong> or Facebook, depending on where your customers are most active</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Monitoring across platforms</h3>
        <p>Use aggregation tools (BrightLocal, ReviewTrackers, Podium) to monitor sentiment across all platforms in one dashboard. A dip on one platform that doesn't match others often signals a localized service issue worth investigating.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Platform comparison — where review diversity adds most value</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Platform</th><th>Local SEO impact</th><th>Independent traffic</th><th>Solicitation rules</th><th>Priority</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
