        <h2 id="examples">Review diversity in practice — two real examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Law firm: zero to 30 Avvo reviews in 4 months</h3>
        <p>A personal injury firm had 180 Google reviews (4.7 stars) but zero presence on Avvo. Avvo has its own search engine that personal injury prospects use specifically to verify attorney credentials. After building out their Avvo profile and adding it to their review request sequence, they accumulated 30 Avvo reviews (4.9 stars) within 4 months — generating a referral traffic channel that didn't exist before, without changing their Google strategy at all.</p>

        <h3>2. Restaurant: concentrated profile meets Yelp's filter</h3>
        <p>A restaurant with 400 Google reviews and only 2 Yelp reviews discovered that Yelp's recommendation algorithm was filtering the 2 positive Yelp reviews it did have (classifying them as potentially solicited, since they came in suddenly after the owner asked for them). The result: a nearly empty Yelp profile despite being the highest-rated restaurant on Google in their area. After diversifying across Yelp, TripAdvisor, and Facebook through organic discovery rather than direct asks, they built a more resilient multi-platform presence.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Review diversity vs review generation — understanding the relationship</h2>
        <p>These two practices work together but are not the same thing.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Review generation focuses on</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Volume — getting more total reviews</li>
              <li>Velocity — maintaining a steady flow</li>
              <li>Timing — asking at the right moment</li>
              <li>Conversion — asking in a way that gets responses</li>
              <li>Single primary platform (usually Google)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Review diversity focuses on</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Distribution — spreading reviews across platforms</li>
              <li>Resilience — not depending on any single platform</li>
              <li>Citation breadth — building signals across the web</li>
              <li>Industry authority — presence where buyers look</li>
              <li>Multi-platform monitoring and management</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for building review diversity</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prioritize Google first, always.</strong> Google reviews have the most direct impact on local pack rankings. Build volume there before spreading to other platforms.</li>
          <li><strong>Add platforms one at a time.</strong> Launching review requests on five platforms simultaneously divides customer attention and reduces total conversion. Add a new platform to your request sequence only after the previous one is performing consistently.</li>
          <li><strong>Never ask for Yelp reviews directly.</strong> Yelp's algorithm actively filters reviews that appear solicited. Make Yelp easy to find through your website and email footer links, but don't direct customers there in review requests.</li>
          <li><strong>Match platform to buyer behavior.</strong> A healthcare provider's patients check Healthgrades. A hotel's guests check TripAdvisor. Prioritize platforms your customers actually use over platforms with theoretical SEO value.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor all platforms from one tool.</strong> Scattered monitoring means missed reviews and slow responses. BrightLocal, ReviewTrackers, and Podium all aggregate multiple platforms into a single inbox.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to reviews on every platform, not just Google.</strong> Unanswered reviews on secondary platforms signal to visitors (and to Google) that the business isn't engaged there.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — chasing platform count instead of platform quality</div>
          <p>Review diversity doesn't mean having a profile on 20 platforms with 3 reviews each. That's platform quantity. Review diversity means having meaningful volume on the 4–5 platforms your customers actually check. Five Healthgrades reviews mean nothing to a restaurant owner whose customers aren't healthcare patients.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common review diversity mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Starting with a secondary platform before dominating Google</strong> — Google's local pack impact is 5–10x higher than any other platform; establish it first</li>
          <li><strong>Directly soliciting Yelp reviews</strong> — Yelp's filter will remove them, creating a false sense of progress</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring industry-specific platforms</strong> — in healthcare, legal, and home services, Healthgrades, Avvo, and Angi send buyer-intent traffic that Google can't match</li>
          <li><strong>Setting up profiles but not monitoring them</strong> — an unmonitored profile accumulates unanswered negative reviews with no context for future customers</li>
          <li><strong>Treating all platforms equally</strong> — Google, Yelp, and Facebook are not equal in impact; allocate review generation effort proportionally</li>
        </ul>

